On Mon, 22 Mar 1999, Jamie Lokier wrote:
> Guy Sotomayor wrote:
> > I don't know where you got the 100MB number from but that would imply
> > a *very* dense drive.  The best I could find was a Seagate Elite at
> > 47GB (not a terribly fast drive) that has ~10000 cylinders (yes 10^4),
> > 28 heads and 328 sectors/track.  Given that sectors are 512 bytes
> > that's ~150KB.
> 
> 28 heads does not sound like a realistic geometry.
Why not? The Elite 47 is a BIG modern (ok, late 1997) 5.25" drive.
Heck, the newer Barracuda 50 puts *22* heads in a 1.6" 3.5" drive... The
Elite 47 is a 3.25" high 5.25" drive that isn't THAT much older...
> And I thought all modern drives varied the number of physical sectors
> per physical track.
> 
> Is 10000/28/328 simply what the drive reports, or do you know it to be
> the actual geometry on the platters?
Some quick checking on Seagate's web-pages[1] gives 9996 cylinders, 28
heads and an AVERAGE of 328 sectors per track. All this is verbatim
from their specification.
(And besides it's easy to verify, the figures checks with the required
number of sectors, which also are listed). 
91923356 / 9996 / 28 = 328.43
1. 
http://www.seagate.com/support/disc/specs/st446452w.shtml
